<div class="content">
  <h2>How the Sourdough Hydration Calculator Works</h2>
  <p>This <strong>sourdough hydration calculator</strong> computes your total dough hydration by accounting for the water content in both your added water and your sourdough starter. Because a starter is a living culture of flour and water, it contributes to both the flour and water totals in your recipe.</p>
  <p>The formula is straightforward: <strong>Hydration % = (Total Water ÷ Total Flour) × 100</strong>. The "total water" includes your added water plus the water portion of your starter. The "total flour" includes your recipe flour plus the flour portion of your starter.</p>

  <h2>Understanding Dough Hydration</h2>
  <p>Hydration is the single most important variable in bread baking. It determines crumb structure, crust texture, oven spring, and how the dough handles during shaping. A <strong>bread hydration calculator</strong> removes the guesswork, especially when working with sourdough starters of varying hydration levels.</p>
  <p>Lower hydration doughs (55–65%) produce tight, even crumbs perfect for sandwich bread and bagels. Mid-range hydration (68–75%) is where most sourdough recipes live — enough moisture for an open crumb without being unmanageable. High hydration doughs (78–88%) produce the coveted large, irregular holes seen in artisan ciabatta and focaccia.</p>

  <h3>Using the Pizza Dough Hydration Calculator</h3>
  <p>For Neapolitan-style pizza, aim for 60–65% hydration with bread flour or tipo 00. New York-style pizza typically uses 58–62%. This <strong>pizza dough hydration calculator</strong> helps you nail the exact water amount whether you're using a sourdough starter or commercial yeast (just set starter weight to 0).</p>

  <h3>Reverse Mode — Target a Specific Hydration</h3>
  <p>Don't know how much water to add? Switch to "Target Hydration" mode. Enter your desired hydration percentage, flour weight, and starter details — the calculator tells you exactly how many grams of water to add. This is especially useful when adapting recipes for different flour types or scaling batches.</p>

