    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">What is dough hydration percentage?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">Dough hydration percentage is the ratio of total water weight to total flour weight in a bread recipe, expressed as a percentage. For example, if you use 750g of water and 1000g of flour, your hydration is 75%. This includes water contributed by the sourdough starter.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">How do I calculate hydration with a sourdough starter?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">A sourdough starter is a mix of flour and water. A 100% hydration starter is equal parts flour and water by weight. To calculate total hydration, split the starter into its flour and water components: a 200g starter at 100% hydration contributes 100g flour and 100g water. Add those to your recipe's flour and water totals, then divide total water by total flour.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">What hydration is best for sourdough bread?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">Most sourdough bread recipes use 70–78% hydration. Beginners should start around 70–72% for easier handling. As you gain experience with wet doughs, you can move toward 75–78% for a more open crumb. Higher hydrations (80%+) produce artisan-style loaves with large irregular holes but require strong shaping skills.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">What is the difference between 65% and 85% hydration dough?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">A 65% hydration dough is stiff and easy to shape — ideal for bagels, pizza, and sandwich bread. An 85% hydration dough is very wet, sticky, and slack — it produces ciabatta-style bread with large, irregular air pockets and a thin, crispy crust. Higher hydration doughs require stretch-and-fold techniques rather than traditional kneading.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">Does starter hydration matter for the final dough?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">Yes. Starter hydration changes how much flour vs. water it contributes. A 100% hydration starter is 50/50 flour and water. A stiff starter at 60% hydration contributes more flour and less water, lowering your overall dough hydration. Always account for starter hydration when calculating your final dough hydration.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">How do I adjust hydration for whole wheat or rye flour?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">Whole wheat and rye flours absorb significantly more water than white bread flour due to higher bran and fiber content. When substituting whole grain flours, increase hydration by 5–10% to achieve a similar dough consistency. For example, if a white flour recipe calls for 72% hydration, use 77–82% hydration with whole wheat.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

